FROM SORRTRM, SOBTERM a, STVTERM
where trunc(SYSDATE) between SORRTRM_START_DATE And SORRTRM_END_DATE
and SORRTRM_TERM_CODE = STVTERM_CODE
and SORRTRM_TERM_CODE = a.SOBTERM_TERM_CODE
and a.SOBTERM_TERM_CODE = c.SOBTERM_TERM_CODE

Look for a term with a category of 'subterm' with the same TERM.REPORTING.YEAR and a lower TERM.SEQUENCE.NO than the current term.
If none is found, find the subterm with a category of 'subterm' in the previous year (TERM.REPORTING.YEAR minus 1) with the highest TERM.SEQUENCE.NO.
This is always the enumeration of notAllowed since  Colleague allows dates to be overriden at the section level rather than at the term level.

If TERM.SESSION is not null and it points to a SESSIONS record that has SESS.INTG.CATEGORY populated, use that as the category (year, term, subterm).Otherwise, If the TERM.REPORTING.TERM is not equal to the TERMS.ID then publish 'subterm' indicating a non-reporting term

For a TERMS record with the category of 'term', if TERM.REPORTING.TERM points to a TERM where TERM.SESSION is not null and the SESSIONS record has SESS.INTG.CATEGORY of 'year', publish that TERMS GUID.
For a TERMS record with the category of 'term', if no TERMS record to publish as the category.parent.academicPeriod.id then publish TERMS.REPORTING.YEAR

Look for a reporting term with a category of 'term' with the same TERM.REPORTING.YEAR and a lower TERM.SEQUENCE.NO than the current term.
If none is found, find the reporting term with a category of 'term' in the previous year (TERM.REPORTING.YEAR minus 1) with the highest TERM.SEQUENCE.NO.

If TERM.SESSION is not null and it points to a SESSIONS record that has SESS.INTG.CATEGORY populated, use that as the category (year, term, subterm).  Otherwise, if the TERM.REPORTING.TERM is equal to the TERMS.ID, then publish 'term' which indicates a reporting term.
If TERM.SESSION is not null and it points to a SESSIONS record that has SESS.INTG.CATEGORY populated, use that as the category (year, term, subterm).

To identify a term as 'open', the API request date is greater than or equal to the earliest registration start date specified on ACTM (e.g. preregistration start, registration start, add period start, etc.) << AND >> less than or equal to the latest date specified on ACTM (e.g. preregistration end, registration end, add period end, drop period end, etc.).

A term would be 'closed' if the API request date is less than the earliest date specified on ACTM (e.g. preregistration start, registration start, add period start, etc.) << AND >> greater than the latest date specified on ACTM (e.g. preregistration end, registration end, add period end, drop period end, etc.).

If no registration dates are specified at the term level, the registration property is omitted from the response.

This API validates an accounting string for a transaction in progress and optionally confirms that the accounting string has sufficient budget for the amount being entered. If date is not sent in the GET URL, system date is considered. An accounting string is a delimited combination of components such as Chart, Index, Fund, Organization, Account, Program, Activity, Location, Rule class, Bank code. The GET URL expects an accountingString and amount to be sent for the API to return a response.When accounting string and amount validation passes, the API returns back the accounting-string JSON in the response.If the accounting string validation fails, the API returns appropriate error message.
The date for which the availability of funds was evaluated for an accounting string.

Status of the availability of funds for an accounting string. The API displays 'available' or 'notAvailable' based on the value returned by NSF package response. If the submittedBy User was included in the filter, and request User has a FOBPROF record with "NSF Override" authority active, then the response returned should be overrideAvailable instead of (budget) notAvailable if the NSF package response returned is Insufficient Funds.

While determining subcomponent.id, we find the ACCT.STRUCTURE.INTG record of the subcomponent. ASI.PARENT tells us the subcomponent name of the parent.
If ASI.PARENT is null, this subcomponent has no parent and returns nothing.
Otherwise, read the ACCT.STRUCTURE.INTG record keyed by ASI.PARENT and get ASI.LENGTH. Truncate the ID to that number of characters.
If a record/GUID in XX.DESCS (ASI.FILE.NAME) for that subcomponent exists, then return its GUID.
If no such record/GUID exists, then return an error which includes the ACCT.SUB.NAME of the parent component (ACCT.STRUCTURE.INTG.ID).

An accounting string is a delimited combination of components such as Chart, Index, Fund, Organization, Account, Program, Activity, Location, Rule class, Bank code. The GET URL expects an accountingString to be sent for the API to return a response. If the accounting string sent is valid, then API returns back the accounting-string JSON in the response. If the accounting string validation fails, the API returns appropriate error message.

To identify a term as 'open', the API request date is greater than or equal to the earliest registration start date specified on ACTM (e.g. preregistration start, registration start, add period start, etc.) << AND >> less than or equal to the latest date specified on ACTM (e.g. preregistration end, registration end, add period end, drop period end, etc.).

A term would be 'closed' if the API request date is less than the earliest date specified on ACTM (e.g. preregistration start, registration start, add period start, etc.) << AND >> greater than the latest date specified on ACTM (e.g. preregistration end, registration end, add period end, drop period end, etc.).

If no registration dates are specified at the term level, the registration property is omitted from the response.

This API validates an accounting string for a transaction in progress and optionally confirms that the accounting string has sufficient budget for the amount being entered. If date is not sent in the GET URL, system date is considered. An accounting string is a delimited combination of components such as Chart, Index, Fund, Organization, Account, Program, Activity, Location, Rule class, Bank code. The GET URL expects an accountingString and amount to be sent for the API to return a response.When accounting string and amount validation passes, the API returns back the accounting-string JSON in the response.If the accounting string validation fails, the API returns appropriate error message.
The date for which the availability of funds was evaluated for an accounting string.

Status of the availability of funds for an accounting string. The API displays 'available' or 'notAvailable' based on the value returned by NSF package response. If the submittedBy User was included in the filter, and request User has a FOBPROF record with "NSF Override" authority active, then the response returned should be overrideAvailable instead of (budget) notAvailable if the NSF package response returned is Insufficient Funds.

If not specified, return the current system date and time.

While determining subcomponent.id, we find the ACCT.STRUCTURE.INTG record of the subcomponent. ASI.PARENT tells us the subcomponent name of the parent.
If ASI.PARENT is null, this subcomponent has no parent and returns nothing.
Otherwise, read the ACCT.STRUCTURE.INTG record keyed by ASI.PARENT and get ASI.LENGTH. Truncate the ID to that number of characters.
If a record/GUID in XX.DESCS (ASI.FILE.NAME) for that subcomponent exists, then return its GUID.
If no such record/GUID exists, then return an error which includes the ACCT.SUB.NAME of the parent component (ACCT.STRUCTURE.INTG.ID).
GUID for ACCT.STRUCTURE.INTG record with ASI.FILE.NAME equal to this GUID's file name and ASI.LENGTH equal to the length of the record.

To identify a term as 'open', the API request date is greater than or equal to the earliest registration start date specified on ACTM (e.g. preregistration start, registration start, add period start, etc.) << AND >> less than or equal to the latest date specified on ACTM (e.g. preregistration end, registration end, add period end, drop period end, etc.).

A term would be 'closed' if the API request date is less than the earliest date specified on ACTM (e.g. preregistration start, registration start, add period start, etc.) << AND >> greater than the latest date specified on ACTM (e.g. preregistration end, registration end, add period end, drop period end, etc.).

This API validates an accounting string for a transaction in progress and optionally confirms that the accounting string has sufficient budget for the amount being entered. If date is not sent in the GET URL, system date is considered. An accounting string is a delimited combination of components such as Chart, Index, Fund, Organization, Account, Program, Activity, Location, Rule class, Bank code. The GET URL expects an accountingString and amount to be sent for the API to return a response.When accounting string and amount validation passes, the API returns back the accounting-string JSON in the response.If the accounting string validation fails, the API returns appropriate error message.
The date for which the availability of funds was evaluated for an accounting string.

Status of the availability of funds for an accounting string. The API displays 'available' or 'notAvailable' based on the value returned by NSF package response. If the submittedBy User was included in the filter, and request User has a FOBPROF record with "NSF Override" authority active, then the response returned should be overrideAvailable instead of (budget) notAvailable if the NSF package response returned is Insufficient Funds.

While determining subcomponent.id, we find the ACCT.STRUCTURE.INTG record of the subcomponent. ASI.PARENT tells us the subcomponent name of the parent.
If ASI.PARENT is null, this subcomponent has no parent and returns nothing.
Otherwise, read the ACCT.STRUCTURE.INTG record keyed by ASI.PARENT and get ASI.LENGTH. Truncate the ID to that number of characters.
If a record/GUID in XX.DESCS (ASI.FILE.NAME) for that subcomponent exists, then return its GUID.
If no such record/GUID exists, then return an error which includes the ACCT.SUB.NAME of the parent component (ACCT.STRUCTURE.INTG.ID).

select nvl((select 'open'
FROM SORRTRM, SOBTERM a, STVTERM
where trunc(SYSDATE) between SORRTRM_START_DATE And SORRTRM_END_DATE
and SORRTRM_TERM_CODE = STVTERM_CODE
and SORRTRM_TERM_CODE = a.SOBTERM_TERM_CODE
and a.SOBTERM_TERM_CODE = c.SOBTERM_TERM_CODE
and a.SOBTERM_DYNAMIC_SCHED_TERM_IND = 'Y'
and a.SOBTERM_REG_ALLOWED = 'Y'),'closed') from SOBTERM c;

To identify a term as 'open', the API request date is greater than or equal to the earliest registration start date specified on ACTM (e.g. preregistration start, registration start, add period start, etc.) << AND >> less than or equal to the latest date specified on ACTM (e.g. preregistration end, registration end, add period end, drop period end, etc.).

A term would be 'closed' if the API request date is less than the earliest date specified on ACTM (e.g. preregistration start, registration start, add period start, etc.) << AND >> greater than the latest date specified on ACTM (e.g. preregistration end, registration end, add period end, drop period end, etc.).

If no registration dates are specified at the term level, the registration property is omitted from the response.

This API validates an accounting string for a transaction in progress and optionally confirms that the accounting string has sufficient budget for the amount being entered. If date is not sent in the GET URL, system date is considered. An accounting string is a delimited combination of components such as Chart, Index, Fund, Organization, Account, Program, Activity, Location, Rule class, Bank code. The GET URL expects an accountingString and amount to be sent for the API to return a response.When accounting string and amount validation passes, the API returns back the accounting-string JSON in the response.If the accounting string validation fails, the API returns appropriate error message.
The date for which the availability of funds was evaluated for an accounting string.

Status of the availability of funds for an accounting string. The API displays 'available' or 'notAvailable' based on the value returned by NSF package response. If the submittedBy User was included in the filter, and request User has a FOBPROF record with "NSF Override" authority active, then the response returned should be overrideAvailable instead of (budget) notAvailable if the NSF package response returned is Insufficient Funds.

While determining subcomponent.id, we find the ACCT.STRUCTURE.INTG record of the subcomponent. ASI.PARENT tells us the subcomponent name of the parent.
If ASI.PARENT is null, this subcomponent has no parent and returns nothing.
Otherwise, read the ACCT.STRUCTURE.INTG record keyed by ASI.PARENT and get ASI.LENGTH. Truncate the ID to that number of characters.
If a record/GUID in XX.DESCS (ASI.FILE.NAME) for that subcomponent exists, then return its GUID.
If no such record/GUID exists, then return an error which includes the ACCT.SUB.NAME of the parent component (ACCT.STRUCTURE.INTG.ID).

This API validates an accounting string for a given date. If date is not sent in the GET URL, system date is considered. An accounting string is a delimited combination of components such as Chart, Index, Fund, Organization, Account, Program, Activity, Location, Rule class, Bank code. The GET URL expects an accountingString to be sent for the API to return a response. If the accounting string sent is valid, then API returns back the accounting-string JSON in the response. If the accounting string validation fails, the API returns appropriate error message.

To identify a term as 'open', the API request date is greater than or equal to the earliest registration start date specified on ACTM (e.g. preregistration start, registration start, add period start, etc.) << AND >> less than or equal to the latest date specified on ACTM (e.g. preregistration end, registration end, add period end, drop period end, etc.).

A term would be 'closed' if the API request date is less than the earliest date specified on ACTM (e.g. preregistration start, registration start, add period start, etc.) << AND >> greater than the latest date specified on ACTM (e.g. preregistration end, registration end, add period end, drop period end, etc.).

If no registration dates are specified at the term level, the registration property is omitted from the response.

This API validates an accounting string for a transaction in progress and optionally confirms that the accounting string has sufficient budget for the amount being entered. If date is not sent in the GET URL, system date is considered. An accounting string is a delimited combination of components such as Chart, Index, Fund, Organization, Account, Program, Activity, Location, Rule class, Bank code. The GET URL expects an accountingString and amount to be sent for the API to return a response.When accounting string and amount validation passes, the API returns back the accounting-string JSON in the response.If the accounting string validation fails, the API returns appropriate error message.
The date for which the availability of funds was evaluated for an accounting string.

If the submittedBy User was included in the filter, and request User has a FOBPROF record with "NSF Override" authority active, then the response returned should be overrideAvailable instead of (budget) notAvailable if the NSF package response returned is Insufficient Funds.

While determining subcomponent.id, we find the ACCT.STRUCTURE.INTG record of the subcomponent. ASI.PARENT tells us the subcomponent name of the parent.
If ASI.PARENT is null, this subcomponent has no parent and returns nothing.
Otherwise, read the ACCT.STRUCTURE.INTG record keyed by ASI.PARENT and get ASI.LENGTH. Truncate the ID to that number of characters.
If a record/GUID in XX.DESCS (ASI.FILE.NAME) for that subcomponent exists, then return its GUID.
If no such record/GUID exists, then return an error which includes the ACCT.SUB.NAME of the parent component (ACCT.STRUCTURE.INTG.ID).

Look for a term with a category of 'subterm' with the same TERM.REPORTING.YEAR and a lower TERM.SEQUENCE.NO than the current term.
If none is found, find the subterm with a category of 'subterm' in the previous year (TERM.REPORTING.YEAR minus 1) with the highest TERM.SEQUENCE.NO.
This is always the enumeration of notAllowed since  Colleague allows dates to be overriden at the section level rather than at the term level.

If TERM.SESSION is not null and it points to a SESSIONS record that has SESS.INTG.CATEGORY populated, use that as the category (year, term, subterm).Otherwise, If the TERM.REPORTING.TERM is not equal to the TERMS.ID then publish 'subterm' indicating a non-reporting term

For a TERMS record with the category of 'term', if TERM.REPORTING.TERM points to a TERM where TERM.SESSION is not null and the SESSIONS record has SESS.INTG.CATEGORY of 'year', publish that TERMS GUID.
For a TERMS record with the category of 'term', if no TERMS record to publish as the category.parent.academicPeriod.id then publish TERMS.REPORTING.YEAR

Look for a reporting term with a category of 'term' with the same TERM.REPORTING.YEAR and a lower TERM.SEQUENCE.NO than the current term.
If none is found, find the reporting term with a category of 'term' in the previous year (TERM.REPORTING.YEAR minus 1) with the highest TERM.SEQUENCE.NO.

To identify a term as 'open', the API request date is greater than or equal to the earliest registration start date specified on ACTM (e.g. preregistration start, registration start, add period start, etc.) << AND >> less than or equal to the latest date specified on ACTM (e.g. preregistration end, registration end, add period end, drop period end, etc.).

A term would be 'closed' if the API request date is less than the earliest date specified on ACTM (e.g. preregistration start, registration start, add period start, etc.) << AND >> greater than the latest date specified on ACTM (e.g. preregistration end, registration end, add period end, drop period end, etc.).

If no registration dates are specified at the term level, the registration property is omitted from the response.

This API validates an accounting string for a transaction in progress and optionally confirms that the accounting string has sufficient budget for the amount being entered. If date is not sent in the GET URL, system date is considered. An accounting string is a delimited combination of components such as Chart, Index, Fund, Organization, Account, Program, Activity, Location, Rule class, Bank code. The GET URL expects an accountingString and amount to be sent for the API to return a response.When accounting string and amount validation passes, the API returns back the accounting-string JSON in the response.If the accounting string validation fails, the API returns appropriate error message.
The date for which the availability of funds was evaluated for an accounting string.

Status of the availability of funds for an accounting string. The API displays 'available' or 'notAvailable' based on the value returned by NSF package response. If the submittedBy User was included in the filter, and request User has a FOBPROF record with "NSF Override" authority active, then the response returned should be overrideAvailable instead of (budget) notAvailable if the NSF package response returned is Insufficient Funds.

While determining subcomponent.id, we find the ACCT.STRUCTURE.INTG record of the subcomponent. ASI.PARENT tells us the subcomponent name of the parent.
If ASI.PARENT is null, this subcomponent has no parent and returns nothing.
Otherwise, read the ACCT.STRUCTURE.INTG record keyed by ASI.PARENT and get ASI.LENGTH. Truncate the ID to that number of characters.
If a record/GUID in XX.DESCS (ASI.FILE.NAME) for that subcomponent exists, then return its GUID.
If no such record/GUID exists, then return an error which includes the ACCT.SUB.NAME of the parent component (ACCT.STRUCTURE.INTG.ID).
